2 individuals appeared to be intersex hens (spontaneous sex reversal). See photos for details. Notes: Male MALL should be in breeding plumage by October, so ruling out eclipse males. Ruling out hybrids (ABDU x MALL, GADW x MALL, NOPI x MALL as hybrid plumages are usually quite distinct and can be seen in field guides). One individual observed across the open water was similar to Sibley’s Drake-plumaged female Northern Mallard. re: smaller in size, darker spot in middle of bill similar to female, green drake head colouring on the majority of head but with female looking body, for the majority. Second individual had some female plumage features on the body (mixed with male features) but almost all green head, with dark green cheek. One section of face between eye and bill lacking green. Bill looking almost entirely male which is not typical of intersex hens from what I could find in my limited research.

Observation Details: While trimming a shrub at the edge of the prairie patch in my front yard, I flushed a female Mallard incubating eggs. She was reluctant to leave and hesitated even exposing the full clutch, so presumably the eggs are getting close to hatching. We have seen a pair of Mallards in the area on occasion, and a female in our yard once in awhile, but had no idea this nest was here. The lawnmower would have come within a metre or so of the nest on at least a couple of occasions and there was no indication the nest was there. It appeared that there was likely about 8 eggs. Update: she left the nest briefly and when I checked, counted 9 eggs.

Observation Details: Photo shows a male Mallard that at very first glance I dismissively thought was a female, since a  breeding-plumaged drake was also seen on this outing. This mallard, alone off by itself, came quietly limping up the incline from the small wetland at the back of the park, and ended up standing only two feet away from me where I was sitting on a nearby bench (presumedly it was hoping for a handout). Very skulky, very quiet, and after it realized I had no food, it quietly limped back down to disappear into the cattails. Not being that familiar with mallard molt timing in SE Arizona, but thinking that it seemed awfully early for eclipse plumage, I though AFTERWARDS that perhaps it might be Mexican Mallard or a hybrid. It is not - despite the time of year (AZ birds may simply molt sooner due to an earlier breeding season?) all characteristics are those of Northern Mallard: green in crown, gray cheeks with black flecks (no tan), olive-tinted yellow bill, back/covert feathers edged with buff (not cinnamon), and although at the time I didn't even think to take photos of the tail, it had white tail feathers and two mildly-curled black feathers. (It didn't seem to be a youngster, since it had the clear, pale adult bill).

2 individuals appeared to be intersex hens (spontaneous sex reversal). See photos for details. Notes: Male MALL should be in breeding plumage by October, so ruling out eclipse males. Ruling out hybrids (ABDU x MALL, GADW x MALL, NOPI x MALL as hybrid plumages are usually quite distinct and can be seen in field guides). One individual observed across the open water was similar to Sibley’s Drake-plumaged female Northern Mallard. re: smaller in size, darker spot in middle of bill similar to female, green drake head colouring on the majority of head but with female looking body, for the majority. Second individual had some female plumage features on the body (mixed with male features) but almost all green head, with dark green cheek. One section of face between eye and bill lacking green. Bill looking almost entirely male which is not typical of intersex hens from what I could find in my limited research.

Observation Details: Not much to be confident about on this bird other than it appears to have Mallard in it and doesn't appear to be dark enough for a Mexican (maybe not even dark enough for a classic hybrid?). At any other time of year, this would not warrant a second glance as half the Mallards on the river look like this but, at this time of year, a green-billed female plumaged Mallard deserved attention. The combination of green bill, brown undertail coverts, creamy brown outertail (probably too pale) and lack of tail curl give it a superficial drake Mexican look. However, rest of plumage appears to look fine for a green-billed female Mallard or some sort of Mallard x Cayuga backcross is likely.  I have now found 2 other "brown" Mallards at this location this week with some hints of green in the bill (one darker-billed bird with a small dark green bill tip and another greener-billed bird). But neither bird approaching the wholly green bill on this bird and both of them had whitish vents and whitish tails. Based on bill alone, the other 2 birds look close to Mexican type hybrids and slashes from AZ and CO. I'm not sure how common green-billed brown winter Mallards are but I can't seem to find many pics online and those that I do are from places like AZ and CO with Mexican Ducks often in the same picture.  So, something is going on in this stretch of river and likely it's just domestic influence.

Same group as usual, have photos. A couple of drakes being terrible, a couple of drakes defending the hens, one consensual interaction initiated by hen approaching and head bobbing followed by drake. Another drake went after him before he fully mounted her. One hen missing tons of feathers on her head. I've never struggled to watch aggression in birds like I do here. I actually wonder if all of the groups of drakes were dumped here by someone who didn't want to deal with their behavior so it's overrepresented in this group. I've been watching birds here for years and it's never been such constant nonconsensual activity until so many groups of near flightless domestics were dumped.
